    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <head>Biographical History</head>
      <p>Phillips Brooks was an American Episcopal bishop and poet.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
      <p>The









        <emph render="bold">Phillips Brooks Collection</emph>, comprised of writings by Brooks (1835-1895) and memorabilia related to his writings, contains two items from the years 1890 and 1958.  "O Little Town of Bethlehem" is Episcopal bishop Brooks' most famous Christmas poem.</p>
      <p>
        <emph render="bold">Writings</emph> consists of a signed holograph manuscript of a portion of one of Brooks' poems, "A Christmas Carol" (1898).  Written to accompany "A Christmas Carol,"









        <emph render="bold">Memorabilia</emph> contains a 1958 musical score by William Self, choir master and organist for St. Thomas Church in New York.</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <relatedmaterial encodinganalog="544 1">
      <head>Related Material</head>
      <p>Both "A Christmas Carol" and the musical setting were used in George Arents' 1958 Christmas card, a specimen of which is among the Library's rare book collections.</p>
    </relatedmaterial>
